    "body": "We wouldn't normally need to worry about having \"parity\" features, I know @heaths isn't a fan, but we actually have specific logic to configure support for invalid certificates, and don't currently expose the `reqwest::ClientBuilder` to configure. So, in order to expose our own APIs to allow support for invalid certificates (commonly needed when working with the emulator), this PR introduces an explicit `native-tls` feature.\r\n\r\nUsers don't necessarily have to use this parity feature. They could actually just disable default features (thus getting a `reqwest` with no TLS backend feature enabled, since we bring `reqwest` in without default features too) and then use feature unification to bring `native-tls` in (as @heaths prefers). The only thing they actually need to use our features for is to expose _our TLS configuration APIs_. Today, that's just allowing invalid certificates, but in future it may include other things.\r\n\r\nWe implement this using an internal, by convention, feature `__tls`, which is the same as how `reqwest` itself does. Each TLS backend feature (`native-tls` and `rustls`) enables this feature, and the APIs are gated on that feature. This allows us to keep the feature gating attributes minimal and makes it easier to add new APIs and new backend features when needed.\r\n\r\nIncluded is a sample in the top-level `samples/` directory that shows disabling the `rustls` default and enabling `native-tls`",
